[[Category:Ancient currencies]]

{{for|the first-century bishop|Anianus of Alexandria}} '''Annianus of Alexandria''' ({{lang-grc-gre|italic=yes|Annianos)}} was a monk who flourished in [[Alexandria]] during the [[bishop]]ric of [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria|Theophilus of Alexandria]] around the beginning of the fifth century. He criticized the world history of his contemporary monk [[Panodorus of Alexandria]] for relying too much on secular sources rather than biblical sources for his dates.
As a result, Annianus developed his own [[chronology]] which placed [[Dating Creation|Creation]] on 25 March 5492 BC. This created the Alexandrian Era whose first day was the first day of the [[proleptic calendar|proleptic]] Alexandrian civil year in progress, 29 August 5493 BC. This year was eleven Paschal cycles of 532 years each before the Alexandrian year beginning 29 August 360, which itself was four [[Metonic cycle|19-year cycles]] after the [[epoch (reference date)|epoch]] of the Diocletian Era on 29 August 284. The former is known as the Era of Grace in the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]], whereas the latter is known as the [[Era of Martyrs]]. He was the first [[computus|computist]] to recognize the 532-year cycle of [[Easter]]s in the [[Julian calendar]]. This cycle is often attributed to [[Victorius of Aquitaine|Victorius]] of [[Aquitaine]] in 457, the first to recognize such a cycle in the West.
None of Annianus's writings have survived. He is principally known from the discussion of his works by [[George Syncellus]] during the 9th century, though lesser fragments appear elsewhere. [[Elijah of Nisibis]] cites him in his 11th-century ''Chronography''.{{sfn|Mosshammer|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=0umDqPOf2L8C&pg=PA359 359]}}
==References== ===Citations=== {{reflist|30em}} ===Bibliography=== *William Adler. ''Time immemorial: archaic history and its sources in Christian chronography from Julius Africanus to George Syncellus''. Washington, D.C.: Dumbarton Oaks Research Library and Collection, c1989. *William Adler, Paul Tuffin, translators. ''The chronography of George Synkellos: a Byzantine chronicle of universal history from the creation''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2002. Synkellos copied large blocks of text written by Annianus. {{Authority control}} [[Category:Byzantine theologians]] [[Category:Byzantine historians]] [[Category:5th-century historians]] [[Category:5th-century Byzantine people]] [[Category:Egyptian Christian monks]] [[Category:Egyptian historians of religion]] [[Category:5th-century Byzantine writers]] [[Category:5th-century Christian theologians]]
