'''Richard Indreko''' ({{OldStyleDate|25 February|1900|13 February}}<ref name=birth>{{cite web|last=Nurk|first=Ragnar|title=Richard Indreko teooria soomeugrilaste etnogeneesist|url=http://www.hot.ee/r/ragnarnurk/failid/Richard%20Indreko.doc|accessdate=14 September 2013|page=5|language=Estonian|year=2005}}</ref> in [[Puiatu, Paide Parish|Puiatu]], Purdi parish, [[Järvamaa]] – 10 March 1961 in [[Stockholm]]) was an [[Estonia]]n [[historian]] and [[archaeologist]]. He is noted for his research into ancient Estonian history.
From 1923-1927 he studied at the [[University of Tartu]] and became a lecturer there in 1933. From 1933 to 1937 he led the excavations in the Kunda Lammasmäel ja Asvas. He conducted important research into the ''[[Proto-Uralic homeland hypotheses|Origin and Area of Settlement of the Finno-Ugrian peoples]]''.<ref>[http://www.kirj.ee/public/trames/zvelebil.htm www.kirj.ee]</ref>
In 1941 he published "Mid Stone Age in Estonia" ("Keskmine kiviaeg Eestis"). In 1943 he fled to [[Finland]] and settled a year later in [[Sweden]]. He died in [[Stockholm]] in 1961. Shortly afterwards his ''Prehistoric Age of Estonia'' was published in 1962.<ref>[http://openlibrary.org/b/OL20238320M/Prehistoric_age_of_Estonia Open Library]</ref>
